A better year for migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the migration crisis in the Mediterranean.
First, Europe and the international community are applying a cruelly ill-suited system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants.
Second, in the face of the inefficiency of this system, populist actors continue to exploit fears in order to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies whose construction required some 70 years of determined effort.
This is why it is essential that a truly active initiative be undertaken this year at both the European and global levels.
In September, United Nations Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit aimed at building a solid global system for the protection of the most vulnerable migrants and refugees.
Let us hope that states will be ready to commit in a concrete and sustainable manner.
This necessary commitment was sorely lacking during the year 2015.
In fact, the international community could have limited the severity of last year's crisis if it had provided even the most modest support to frontline countries – Turkey, Lebanon, and Jordan – which together host no less than four million refugees.
With only about 10 billion euros, these countries would have been better able to house, feed, and provide education to refugees, thereby reducing the temptation to flee to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany alone up to 21 billion € each year in the coming years.
But the financial implications of the crisis are nothing compared to its human and political cost.
More than a million people risked their lives last year crossing the Mediterranean, enduring a grueling journey through the Balkans afterwards.
Nearly 4,000 migrants lost their lives there, while many European countries turned their backs on the survivors by refusing to grant them refuge.
The most cynical political actors have mercilessly exploited citizens' fears, promoting a hateful nationalist vision that either ignores or distorts the lived experiences of migrants.
In the United States, for example, not a single one of the 780,000 refugees settled since September 11, 2001, has been found guilty of terrorist acts.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more in taxes than they receive in social benefits.
And yet, extremist parties are dangerously flirting with gaining political power in some European countries, and are currently gaining support within once-liberal strongholds.
Anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success also leads traditional parties to promote an immigration-hostile policy as well.
This situation has significantly undermined European cooperation.
The EU program aimed at dealing with the million refugees who arrived on its shores has only managed to "relocate" 190 of them.
Border controls in six countries within the Schengen area have been reinstated, at least temporarily.
In the eyes of the rest of the world, the EU appears today chauvinistic and incompetent.
Of course, resolving this crisis concerns not only Europe; responsibility cannot be defined simply by geographical proximity.
No matter what, the EU is undoubtedly facing today a threat to its own existence, which it will only be able to overcome by firmly demonstrating the solidarity and international leadership it is capable of.
That is why it is up to member states to take the initiative by proposing solutions.
The most urgent priority is to establish legal and secure pathways allowing refugees to reach Europe.
This does not mean asserting that every distressed migrant must be welcomed.
Nevertheless, the EU must be more systematically generous in determining the number of refugees to welcome, and use orderly mechanisms aimed at facilitating their entry.
Such a system would protect migrants while safeguarding Europe (through the possibility of fully examining applications).
Beyond an approach aimed at deterring asylum seekers from risking their lives by crossing the Mediterranean, this approach would project an image of solidarity toward frontline countries, which continue to host the majority of refugees.
Equally important, this approach would encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to the efforts.
This leads us to the second priority of 2016: building a robust global system for the protection of vulnerable refugees and migrants.
This goal will first require that more countries agree to accept refugees.
In recent years, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees has only managed to resettle less than 75,000 of the approximately 20 million annual refugees.
Millions of them end up in a situation of prolonged migration, with an average duration estimated at 25 years, trapped in a kind of purgatory and uncertain about the day of a possible return to their home country.
In 2016, it is necessary for developed countries to commit to hosting a cumulative number close to one million refugees each year, either through their resettlement or by granting them humanitarian, student, professional, or other visas.
Since Canada has stated that it will alone welcome 50,000 Syrian refugees this year, this is a clearly achievable goal.
At the same time, the international community will need to support the integration of refugees in major host countries such as Turkey, Kenya, Lebanon, and Jordan.
As it stands, these countries receive only a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually needed per refugee for housing, food, care, education, and vocational training during the first years of settlement.
And these figures do not take into account the necessary cost of building or upgrading infrastructure.
In Lebanon, for example, water supply systems are suffering from the pressure caused by the massive arrival of refugees.
In exchange for funding, host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor markets, and civic institutions.
But effective integration of migrants will only be possible if countries in Europe and elsewhere get rid of their prejudices regarding migrants.
If migrants are still seen as a burden, or even a threat to security, reactionary political forces will continue to gain ground, depriving newcomers of opportunities and turning fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
On the other hand, if host countries manage to integrate migrants enthusiastically, everyone will benefit – including these countries (notably through remittances).
Last month, in Paris, the international community proved that it was capable of subordinating its national interests to a broader global goal: the fight against climate change.
In 2016, a similar effort is needed to build a better protection system for migrants.
This is a matter of life or death for some 20 million refugees, for several million other vulnerable migrants – and also a profound test of the civic health of democratic societies around the world.
